answer.para:
These are all very important issues because telecommunications costs are the second&hyphen;

 largest cost input for most businesses after wages and salaries and, unless you have an efficient Telstra, unless it is able to compete against newcomers into the game, it will be very much handicapped. You put management in positions to make those hard decisions. No&hyphen;one gets any joy out of reducing labour in whatever sector it might be, but if there is one industry in which you would like to be if your job were at risk, it would be in a sector where the growth rate is about 18 per cent. The telecommunications industry is growing at that level and, as Ian McLean himself said, if jobs go from Telstra, they are likely to go to the private sector—in other words, you can confidently expect that there will be a huge demand for jobs from the telecommunications industry. That was said by SPAN and ATUG to the Senate committee. I am sorry that you chose to ignore that because it is very important evidence. To the extent that people are unable to be employed by Telstra, their prospects of being employed elsewhere are very good. And that is one of the great virtues of this industry and why you want to have as much efficiency as possible.

  (Time expired)

